text=:Category: PracticeCategory%0a:Title: Deafness and Language%0a:Author: xiranw%0a:Section:B%0a:Completed: 03.02.2021 - 18:04%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a%0a#foxbegin 210205-172817-248730#%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a#foxend 210205-172817-248730#%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210208-145316-885040#%0a* [-08.02.2021 - 06:53-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210208-145316-885040#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhat language(s) do deaf people use when thinking?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhen the question of what constitutes a language came up during class on Monday, a common response from students was that language is a means of communication between humans. But we do not use languages only to communicate to others; we think to ourselves using languages too. The main difference between the two scenarios is that the former tends to be vocal while the latter not. When I think, instead of making sounds, I imagine myself making sounds.%0aThis brings me to my question: when deaf people think, how do they, well, imagine themselves making sounds? Do they perhaps picture the lip and jaw movement? Do they think in sign language? On a related note, I also wonder what languages babies use when thinking. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
