diff:1612404257:1612404257:=1,40d0%0a%3c :Category: PracticeCategory%0a%3c :Title: Deafness and Language%0a%3c :Author: xiranw%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 03.02.2021 - 18:04%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c What language(s) do deaf people use when thinking?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c When the question of what constitutes a language came up during class on Monday, a common response from students was that language is a means of communication between humans. But we do not use languages only to communicate to others; we think to ourselves using languages too. The main difference between the two scenarios is that the former tends to be vocal while the latter not. When I think, instead of making sounds, I imagine myself making sounds.%0a%3c This brings me to my question: when deaf people think, how do they, well, imagine themselves making sounds? Do they perhaps picture the lip and jaw movement? Do they think in sign language? On a related note, I also wonder what languages babies use when thinking. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
